\b AccrediCore Main Local Recovery Summary\par
\b0
This document summarizes what was missing after the Supabase export/import process and what was added or repaired so the project can run locally as a customer-managed deployment.\par
\par
\b 1. Initial Problem After Export From Supabase\par
\b0
When the application source was moved into the local repository, the frontend code was present but the full local runtime parity was not. The main gaps were:\par
\par
\bullet \tab The frontend still depended on a hardcoded Supabase cloud project instead of a configurable local backend.\par
\bullet \tab The local PostgreSQL database did not contain the full set of tables used by the frontend.\par
\bullet \tab Several RPC/database functions used by the UI were missing locally.\par
\bullet \tab Storage, auth behavior, edge functions, and authorization rules were incomplete or inconsistent in the local environment.\par
\bullet \tab Governance features such as approval chain, audit trail, version archive, notifications, and attestation were not fully represented in the local stack.\par
\bullet \tab Customer-ready local packaging was incomplete.\par
\par
\b 2. What Commonly Gets Lost When Moving From Supabase Cloud To Local\par
\b0
The following categories are the main items that were effectively missing or incomplete and had to be rebuilt or verified:\par
\par
\bullet \tab Table coverage parity between frontend queries and the local database.\par
\bullet \tab Custom RPC functions referenced by hooks, contexts, and pages.\par
\bullet \tab Row Level Security and role-based access rules.\par
\bullet \tab Storage bucket setup and read/write policy behavior.\par
\bullet \tab Edge functions such as create-user and update-user-password.\par
\bullet \tab Auth-related compatibility objects needed for local operation.\par
\bullet \tab Seed users and role records for realistic smoke/manual testing.\par
\bullet \tab Governance objects: approval requests, versioning, audit logs, notifications, policy attestations.\par
\bullet \tab Documentation and setup scripts required for customer-local deployment.\par
\par
\b 3. Main Recovery Work Completed\par
\b0
\par
\b 3.1 Frontend Environment Decoupling\par
\b0
The frontend client was changed so it no longer depends on a hardcoded cloud URL/key and can be pointed to local Supabase using environment variables.\par
\par
Relevant area:\par
{\f1 app-source/src/integrations/supabase/client.ts}\par
\par
\b 3.2 Database Contract Recovery\par
\b0
The local database was rebuilt incrementally through staged SQL patches and a final schema dump. This restored the frontend-facing contract that had been missing locally.\par
\par
Key files:\par
{\f1 database/bootstrap/008_phase3_frontend_contract_patch.sql}\par
{\f1 database/bootstrap/009_supabase_local_contract_patch.sql}\par
{\f1 database/bootstrap/local_full_schema_dump.sql}\par
\par
Tables/functions recovered or validated include the main frontend dependencies such as:\par
\par
\bullet \tab profiles\par
\bullet \tab user_roles\par
\bullet \tab teams\par
\bullet \tab team_members\par
\bullet \tab documents\par
\bullet \tab policies\par
\bullet \tab policy_templates\par
\bullet \tab task_comments\par
\bullet \tab task_progress\par
\bullet \tab project_quality_plan\par
\bullet \tab audit_schedules\par
\bullet \tab incidents and related workflow objects\par
\par
Critical RPCs restored/verified locally include:\par
\par
\bullet \tab get_current_user_role\par
\bullet \tab get_department_compliance_summary\par
\bullet \tab update_audit_progress\par
\par
\b 3.3 Authorization Hardening\par
\b0
Local authorization was tightened so the system behaves more like the intended production model. This included RLS-oriented restrictions and UI behavior alignment.\par
\par
Key file:\par
{\f1 database/bootstrap/010_supabase_local_authorization_patch.sql}\par
\par
Examples of results:\par
\par
\bullet \tab Staff users can no longer create policies, teams, or restricted management records.\par
\bullet \tab Staff UI was changed so management actions are hidden or denied where appropriate.\par
\bullet \tab Sensitive modules such as User Management and Team Management now show Access Denied for staff.\par
\bullet \tab Policy Library actions shown to staff were reduced to read-oriented actions only.\par
\par
\b 3.4 Governance and Compliance Workflow Recovery\par
\b0
The local database and UI were extended to support governance workflows that were missing or incomplete.\par
\par
Key files:\par
{\f1 database/bootstrap/011_policy_governance_patch.sql}\par
{\f1 database/bootstrap/012_notification_attestation_patch.sql}\par
\par
Features added/restored:\par
\par
\bullet \tab Policy approval chain\par
\bullet \tab Policy version archive/history\par
\bullet \tab Audit logs backed by real database data\par
\bullet \tab In-app notifications\par
\bullet \tab Staff acknowledgment/attestation\par
\par
Approval sequence implemented:\par
\par
\bullet \tab Team Leader / Super User review\par
\bullet \tab Department Manager approval\par
\bullet \tab System Administrator / Executive approval\par
\par
\b 3.5 Edge Functions and Local Supabase Coverage\par
\b0
The repository already contained Supabase migrations and edge function source, but local parity required additional validation and fixes.\par
\par
Relevant local sources:\par
{\f1 app-source/supabase/config.toml}\par
{\f1 app-source/supabase/migrations/...}\par
{\f1 app-source/supabase/functions/create-user/index.ts}\par
{\f1 app-source/supabase/functions/update-user-password/index.ts}\par
\par
This was important because local customers do not need the internal Supabase platform source code, but they do need the application-owned Supabase assets: migrations, config, functions, and schema patches.\par
\par
\b 3.6 Local API and Audit Support\par
\b0
A lightweight local Express API is included for health checks and selected local PostgreSQL endpoints.\par
\par
Relevant area:\par
{\f1 local-api/server.js}\par
{\f1 local-api/scripts/audit-local-db.js}\par
\par
This was kept as a companion layer for local validation, DB audits, and selected endpoints.\par
\par
\b 3.7 Local Setup, Start, and Validation Scripts\par
\b0
Customer-local scripts were added or organized so a customer IT team can bring the environment up more consistently.\par
\par
Relevant files:\par
{\f1 scripts/setup/setup-env-win.ps1}\par
{\f1 scripts/start/start-win.ps1}\par
{\f1 scripts/health/check-app.ps1}\par
{\f1 scripts/bootstrap/bootstrap-win.ps1}\par
{\f1 docs/local-install/README.md}\par
{\f1 docs/local-install/MANUAL-TEST-GUIDE.md}\par
\par
\b 4. Current Local Capability Achieved\par
\b0
After the recovery work, the local deployment is capable of the following:\par
\par
\bullet \tab Frontend can build and run locally.\par
\bullet \tab Local Supabase-compatible schema is available in bootstrap assets.\par
\bullet \tab Core frontend modules can operate against the local backend contract.\par
\bullet \tab Auth, role checks, storage access, and major workflows have been smoke tested.\par
\bullet \tab Role-based manual testing can be performed with seeded test users.\par
\bullet \tab Governance workflows now exist locally instead of being cloud-only assumptions.\par
\bullet \tab Customer delivery package structure is documented.\par
\par
\b 5. Key Risks / What Was Not Fully Solved By Schema Export Alone\par
\b0
Schema export alone was not enough to produce a usable local product. The following also had to be explicitly addressed:\par
\par
\bullet \tab Frontend environment targeting.\par
\bullet \tab Seed user strategy.\par
\bullet \tab Authorization and UI permission consistency.\par
\bullet \tab Function behavior and edge function authorization.\par
\bullet \tab Governance workflow tables plus UI integration.\par
\bullet \tab Installer and customer-delivery packaging.\par
